author: CHARLOTTE WILLIS
title: The Bachelor Australia 2015: Intruders wreak havoc in mansion
text:
“A RANDOM female in a sparkly dress walks across the grass.” Jaws drop to the floor. Sam’s bachelorettes couldn’t believe their eyes when their new competition entered the mansion during tonight’s drama-filled episode.
Busy toasting themselves for making the final six, a couple of mystery babes — one brunette and one blonde — rocked up to the cocktail party uninvited.

Celebrity 0 comments But Lana Jeavons-Fellows, the first of the date crashers thrown into the lion’s den, says the whole encounter was far more awkward for her.
“Once the reality kind of sunk in that I was going to walk in there with X amount of beautiful girls all trying to date the same guy it was a little bit daunting,” the 27-year-told told news.com.au
“It was awkward, it was so awkward.”
“Not bothered” ... Emily wasn’t feeling threatened at all. But, despite trying not to make too much of a splash — even tiptoeing down the garden stairs to meet the ladies — the NSW-born beauty couldn’t prevent the interrogation from some of her new housemates. One in particular, who made it clear that “intruders are bullshit”.
“I went in there with a smile on my face, I didn’t go in there and try and tear down the fairy lights or blow out the candles or anything,” the communications assistant said.
“I think, once I got in there and I sat down I was like, ‘this is crazy, what am I doing?’”
Sam had no idea the two new ladies were coming. But this year’s top six weren’t the only ones left feeling ambushed, Osher only informed Sam of the two fresh faces moments before their arrival.
And Jeavons-Fellows, who says she “knew absolutely nothing about anyone” and had “no game plan” coming into the mansion, played her ‘first impression’ cards pretty damn well.
The blindsided Bach couldn’t seem to get enough of those beautiful big eyes and told the brunette that she was “a good twist”.
“I think if you have a connection with someone it doesn’t matter whether you met them five weeks ago or five minutes ago, the spark is either there or it’s not,” Jeavons-Fellows said.
Ambushed by a mystery blonde in a sequin dress. The rest of the episode was filled with the kind of chaos we’ve been hanging out for all season: Sarah lands herself a rose.
Bec chin bows out quietly.
Emily blows up, calls Nina “rough” behind her back and then barrels out the front door.
Oh, and blonde intruder Rachel Moore has already been dubbed ‘the crazy cat lady’.
Bring on Thursday night’s episode.
The Bachelor, airs Wednesday and Thursday, 7.30pm on Ten.
Well, this conversation went well ...
